{"count": 28681, "next": "https://api.acmi.net.au/creators/?page=255", "previous": "https://api.acmi.net.au/creators/?page=253", "results": [{"id": 83063, "name": "Jacques Doniol-Vacroze", "roles_in_work": [{"id": 3104998, "title": "L'eau a la Bouche = to Each His Own", "work_id": 116195, "role": "director", "role_id": 938, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 3104798, "title": "La Maison des Bories = the House of the Bories", "work_id": 116086, "role": "director", "role_id": 938, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 3104571, "title": "La Denonciation (Cinemascope Print)", "work_id": 115979, "role": "director", "role_id": 938, "is_primary": true}], "also_known_as": "Jacques Raymond Doniol-Valcroze", "date_of_birth": "1920-03-15", "date_of_death": "1989-10-06", "genders": [{"id": 9, "name": "Male", "slug": "male"}], "languages": [{"id": 4, "name": "French", "slug": "french"}], "places_of_operation": [{"id": 17, "name": "France", "slug": "france"}], "biography": "Jacques Doniol-Valcroze (French: [ʒak dɔnjɔl valkʁoz]; 15 March 1920 – 6 October 1989) was a French actor, critic, screenwriter, and director. In 1951, Doniol-Valcroze was a co-founder of the renowned film magazine Cahiers du cinéma, along with André Bazin and Joseph-Marie Lo Duca. The magazine was initially edited by Doniol-Valcroze between 1951–1957. As critic, he championed numerous filmmakers including Orson Welles, Howard Hawks, and Nicholas Ray.\nIn 1955, then 23-year-old François Truffaut made a short film in Doniol-Valcroze's apartment, Une Visite. Jacques's daughter Florence played a minor part in it.In 1955, he was a member of the jury at the 16th Venice International Film Festival, and in 1964 a member of the jury at the 14th Berlin International Film Festival.", "biography_author": "Wikidata", "date_of_biography": "2023-09-05T20:59:44.265928+10:00", "external_links": [{"id": 2293, "uri": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacques_Doniol-Valcroze"}], "uuid": "e02a36c1-862e-4886-b8ef-62fb6f1f4418", "source": {"name": "Ve